{"key":"post-6899148","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>6899148</id>\n<content>Casing layer sterility has nothing to do with trichoderma.  You're supposed to pasteurize casing material.  If you sterilize it, you raise the risk factor for trich by a factor of at least ten.  Air exchange and proper pasteurization is the key to avoiding trichoderma, not sterility.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition, if the outbreak occured before first flush, the trich was in your spawn or bulk substrate and simply sporulated in the casing layer.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>6913541</next>\n<prev>6898095</prev>\n<first>6897688</first>\n<last>6936482</last>\n<when>1178849021</when>\n<utime>05/11/07 05:03 AM</utime>\n</post>"}